[thinking] **Exploring Spring Boot Configuration**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm diving into the auto-configuration in a Spring Boot app that uses AutoConfigurationPackages for scanning. It seems that with ApplicationContextRunner, I might need to register the AutoConfigurationPackages bean. Using @SpringBootConfiguration in the same package as the test could simplify things, especially regarding nested repositories. It looks like by default, nested repository interfaces aren't considered, which is raised when using @EnableJdbcRepositories. I’m curious how Java handles public and package-private interfaces when scanning. This is quite a puzzle!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Configuring Spring Data JDBC**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm considering creating a UserConfig with the @SpringBootConfiguration annotation to register AutoConfigurationPackages. Then, a top-level package-private PersonRepository could extend CrudRepository. That's fine, and I'll also keep the Person class package-private. Regarding table names, Spring Data JDBC will likely name the table "person" and the ID column "id," with fields like firstName as "first_name." 
[thinking] 
[thinking] I wonder if I should make the entity immutable or use a simpler mutable class. Spring Data JDBC might use a package-private constructor for reflection, which has me thinking about needing metadata for testing under native images. I’m really piecing this together!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Defining Test Structure**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I need to focus on using public classes only while keeping tests with package-private domains. I’m thinking of creating a test called repositoryPersistsUpdatesQueriesAndDeletesAggregate. In this context, I can get JdbcTemplate to execute the creation of a "people" table. 
[thinking] 
[thinking] However, I’ve got to be careful that repository bean creation initializes the mapping before the table is ready. Then, after saving a new Person object, I’ll assert that the ID was assigned. I wonder if querying by name will require a @Query annotation, but I think Spring Data JDBC might support derived queries. This is interesting!
[thinking] 
