HZNlfNygP_zKxXuWal5takQQC18A8i2i7hZVkiKELs2DNMEhKHA4SpfcMm2KLNX4MU1u0g5965Def79TMqld1jXNgSyKBS0BthhbknMp97-r0fbeg6LuYxSYxX6X_wcqGhmdrSCP1P4YdurITNwX2VSogIyAz3BJkJVKKxeL-REa7ITGjHiq590Y74t_VlCu3tdTfvv8pQBlkNZadEQMrJa5rcrFUxd5iydS231KtJQr585MgazMIKI6SoYgkZjCuF_q5abkxBATYwrNp1Dayi8LVslMwONfk4zKUKb3dCLe19vW2xJHF-rgRq8e2fy5nvazgRaDfGwQj9H2rWGMll8lOpZMGnXCOMshDyRuXQjQVYkmxsGblvKCQCCkRszgd_d3Yi_E6JnHdpo77zXHr5L5l7ndwfwQrTcSTOKa6Sp4U-70cW-DMw3bWA0ksengtCANKnV4oI6sNCy-MLpHpiNZBwouA-VjDg_In6kzoXo8-bO5wDC14=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Spring Boot Configuration**\\n\\nI'm diving into the auto-configuration in a Spring Boot app that uses AutoConfigurationPackages for scanning. It seems that with ApplicationContextRunner, I might need to register the AutoConfigurationPackages bean. Using @SpringBootConfiguration in the same package as the test could simplify things, especially regarding nested repositories. It looks like by default, nested repository interfaces aren't considered, which is raised when using @EnableJdbcRepositories. I’m curious how Java handles public and package-private interfaces when scanning. This is quite a puzzle!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Configuring Spring Data JDBC**\\n\\nI'm considering creating a UserConfig with the @SpringBootConfiguration annotation to register AutoConfigurationPackages. Then, a top-level package-private PersonRepository could extend CrudRepository. That's fine, and I'll also keep the Person class package-private. Regarding table names, Spring Data JDBC will likely name the table \\\"person\\\" and the ID column \\\"id,\\\" with fields like firstName as \\\"first_name.\\\" \\n\\nI wonder if I should make the entity immutable or use a simpler mutable class. Spring Data JDBC might use a package-private constructor for reflection, which has me thinking about needing metadata for testing under native images. I’m really piecing this together!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Defining Test Structure**\\n\\nI need to focus on using public classes only while keeping tests with package-private domains. I’m thinking of creating a test called repositoryPersistsUpdatesQueriesAndDeletesAggregate. In this context, I can get JdbcTemplate to execute the creation of a \\\"people\\\" table. \\n\\nHowever, I’ve got to be careful that repository bean creation initializes the mapping before the table is ready. Then, after saving a new Person object, I’ll assert that the ID was assigned. I wonder if querying by name will require a @Query annotation, but I think Spring Data JDBC might support derived queries. This is interesting!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_3ygzrqKrwjL2yGCKFHWyWCPs|fc_0864a54a441f35ff016a0cca41f5c88192902b7048f3a5fbee", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); cd $tmp; curl -sSLO https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/springframework/boot/spring-boot-data-jdbc/4.0.6/spring-boot-data-jdbc-4.0.6.jar; javap -classpath spring-boot-data-jdbc-4.0.6.jar -private -v org.springframework.boot.data.jdbc.autoconfigure.DataJdbcRepositoriesAutoConfiguration | grep -A120 RuntimeVisibleAnnotations", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 662, "output": 815, "cacheRead": 13824, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 15301, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779223093588, "responseId": "resp_0864a54a441f35ff016a0cca35f7f88192ab11d2653e685b05"}}
